{
  "answer": "**In the Old English poem *Deor* (found as Chapter 13 in *Old English Elegies*), there are seven strophes (or stanzas).**[^1]\n\nThe refrain **\"Þæs ofereōde, þisses swā mæg!\"** (translated as **\"That passed over; so may this.\"**) appears at the end of the **first five strophes** and the seventh.[^2][^3] It **ceases after the fifth strophe**, omitted from the sixth (a transitional gnomic reflection on sorrow and divine fortune).[^4] It then resumes once more in the final strophe, where the poet reveals his own plight.[^5]\n\nThus, there are **five strophes before the refrain ceases**.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, Chapter 13 (*Deor*), translation: https://falsafa.corpus/translations/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/13-welund-him-be-wurman-wraeces-cunnade/translation/.\n\n[^2]: Paragraphs [p-1308a0], [p-d11ebc], [p-5821a4], [p-ac23ab], [p-160f1c]: https://falsafa.corpus/translations/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/13-welund-him-be-wurman-wraeces-cunnade/translation/#p-1308a0.\n\n[^3]: Original: https://falsafa.corpus/original/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/13-welund-him-be-wurman-wraeces-cunnade/original/.\n\n[^4]: Paragraph [p-b4d6b7]: https://falsafa.corpus/translations/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/13-welund-him-be-wurman-wraeces-cunnade/translation/#p-b4d6b7.\n\n[^5]: Paragraph [p-6b7e51]: https://falsafa.corpus/translations/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/13-welund-him-be-wurman-wraeces-cunnade/translation/#p-6b7e51.",
